Review: Certainly haunted but not haunted enough. Appreciated the experimental sound, color, and stagnancy. The museum tidying felt it detracted from experimental, lingering ends. Sandra Huller plays a perfect evil mommy
Doofy but the corporate angst was real
So many images. Completely tripping over itself stumbling and loving and schizophrenic. Hard to adore hard to hate just let it melt over like a fever

Compositionally inspiring. By the midway point I felt totally in this like teen boy frustrated hypnotic entrenched groove, and while the plot did drag on, I think it really did take that long to bury all of the characters’ moral philosophies
Gay guys owe me 57 MoviePass credits and 2 hours back

Sad that this movie ended the fun in using the r word when the r word is the perfect word to describe it. Interesting social points but ultimately not a worthwhile endeavor. Looks nice on film but the third act was too nauseating to get their money’s worth on. Sorry

Todd Haynes’ movies rarely have much to say about real life and I will be interested in whether people really think this is iconic in years to come. Too Netflix-ready to be a masterpiece like Carol was, but still so entertaining and dedicated to pervasive discomfort and the humor within

Movie: Don't Eat the Pictures: Sesame Street at the Metropolitan Museum of Art
Review: The little Egyptian boy was beyond annoying and the Sesame Street crew completely carried this, sans Big Bird who was also really annoying. Loved to see the Met advertised through popular culture! Amber was very emotional about it which further moved me
